pthread_create() ... pthread_join() sequence

given the 2 different sequence of function calls, what is the difference in run time or outcome?

1,  	pthread_create(&thread1, NULL, deposit, (void*) &deposit1);
	pthread_create(&thread2, NULL, deposit, (void*) &deposit2);
	
	pthread_join(thread1, NULL);
	pthread_join(thread2, NULL);

2,	pthread_create(&thread1, NULL, deposit, (void*) &deposit1);
	pthread_join(thread1, NULL);
	
	pthread_create(&thread2, NULL, deposit, (void*) &deposit2);
	pthread_join(thread2, NULL);

In sequence 1), both threads are created simultaneously and then joined sequentially. This means that thread1() and thread2() may start executing concurrently, 
potentially leading to a shorter overall runtime if the operations within the threads can be executed concurrently and independently.

In sequence 2), thread1() is joined before thread2() is created. This ensures that thread2() will not start executing until thread1() has completed, potentially leading to a 
longer overall runtime compared to sequence 1) if the operations within the threads are not dependent on each other and could be executed concurrently.

So, the difference in the sequence of function calls can affect the concurrency of execution, potentially impacting the overall runtime of the function.
